# No Community Plugins

When the user asks for a new feature to be created, **never** use Backstage community plugins.

## Policy

- Implement new features in this project, regardless of whether an equivalent community plugin exists.
- Do **not** suggest, install, or integrate external community plugins.
- Do **not** defer to `@backstage-community/*` packages or plugins from the [Backstage community-plugins](https://github.com/backstage/community-plugins) repository.

## What to use instead

- Build custom plugins, modules, and integrations in this repo using official Backstage APIs and core packages (`@backstage/*`).
- Follow the [Backstage Feature Implementation](./backstage-docs.mdc) rule for official docs and conventions.

## Examples

```text
# ❌ BAD — user asks for a cost insights page
"Let's install @backstage-community/plugin-cost-insights"

# ✅ GOOD
"Let's create a custom cost-insights plugin in packages/ using Backstage's plugin APIs"
```

```text
# ❌ BAD — community plugin exists for the requested capability
"The GitHub Actions plugin already exists in the community catalog, so we'll add that dependency."

# ✅ GOOD
"We'll implement this as a first-party plugin in the monorepo, following Backstage plugin structure."
```

## Scope

This applies to **new feature work**. Do not introduce community plugins even if they would save time or match the request closely.
